# Documentation Rules

## Purpose

- Documentation in this repo is a **first-class artifact**, not an afterthought.
- Certain markdown files in `docs/` are treated as the **single source of truth** for product, UX, and technical decisions; **Penpot** is the source of truth for visual UI (linked from the design brief).
- Whenever code changes app behaviour, **relevant docs must be reviewed and updated in the same PR**.

## Canonical documents

Treat these as canonical, not optional:

- Product & UX
  - `docs/01_research.md` – competitive & UX research for DaysTracker.
  - `docs/02_design_brief.md` – product/UX brief, personas, main flows; include a **Penpot file link** when available so screens, components, and tokens are defined in the design tool, not duplicated in markdown.
  - `docs/templates/research_template.md`, `docs/templates/design_brief_template.md` – section structure for drafting/updating the two product docs above (not product truth themselves; change templates when the expected outline changes).

- Visual design (not a markdown file)
  - **Penpot** is the source of truth for UI structure, components, and visual tokens. **`docs/design/assets/`** is for **non-Penpot** files only when explicitly agreed (e.g. map tiles, diagrams). **Do not** store Penpot **screenshots or export PNGs** there — they go stale and are not the design spec.

- Technical architecture
  - `docs/tech/architecture.md` – Clean Architecture, layering, DI, routing, state management rules.
  - `docs/tech/domain_model.md` – domain entities, relationships, enums, invariants.

- Features
  - `docs/features/*.md` – one file per feature (e.g. `visits.md`, `statistics.md`, `background_tracking.md`), with:
    - feature description and scope,
    - UX states and flows,
    - acceptance criteria,
    - important edge cases.

Additional docs (e.g. `CHANGELOG.md`, `ROADMAP.md`, `README.md`) should stay consistent with these canonical files.

## Sync rules between code and docs

- When you change behaviour, data models, or user-visible flows, you **must**:
  - Identify which `docs/features/*.md` and/or tech docs are impacted.
  - Update those documents in the same PR (or explicitly justify why no doc change is needed).
- **Forbidden**: merging a PR that:
  - modifies domain models, repositories, or BLoC behaviour,
  - changes UX flows or adds/removes feature scope,
  - **without** either:
    - updated docs, or
    - a clear note in the PR description: “Docs: no change needed (reason: …)”.
- New features should not be considered “Done” in Linear until:
  - code is merged, and
  - corresponding `docs/features/*.md` exists and reflects the implemented behaviour.

## Structure and style

- All documentation is written in **English**, using clear headings, bullet lists, and short paragraphs.
- Prefer **one place for each fact**:
  - If something belongs in `domain_model.md`, do not duplicate full definitions elsewhere; link or reference instead.
  - Feature-specific rules live in `docs/features/<feature>.md`, higher-level architecture lives in `docs/tech/architecture.md`.
- Keep docs **implementation-oriented but technology-agnostic where possible**:
  - Describe responsibilities, flows, and contracts, not every UI pixel.
  - Avoid leaking low-level implementation details (e.g. function names) into product docs unless necessary.

## Feature doc contents (docs/features/*.md)

Each feature doc should at minimum contain:

- **Overview** – what this feature does and why it exists.
- **User stories / scenarios** – bullet-based flows (happy path + important edge cases).
- **States & UX** – possible UI states (empty, loading, success, error, special cases).
- **Domain impact** – which entities, repositories are involved.
- **Acceptance criteria** – clear, testable statements of “done”.
- **Open questions / future work** – known gaps that are intentionally out of scope for the current iteration.

When implementing or changing a feature, keep this section aligned with the actual code.

## Responsibilities per role/agent

- **Product & UX Strategist / Design agents**:
  - Own and update `01_research.md`, `02_design_brief.md`, and **Penpot** when product/UX or visual design decisions change.
- **Tech Spec & Backlog Architect**:
  - Owns `architecture.md`, `domain_model.md`, and initial `features/*.md`.
- **Dev Feature Agent**:
  - On each PR, checks whether any docs are impacted and proposes updates.
- **Flutter Architecture Guard**:
  - Flags code changes that obviously contradict current `architecture.md` or `domain_model.md` and suggests doc updates when architecture evolves.

## PR checklist (documentation)

Before merging a PR that goes beyond trivial refactors:

- [ ] I reviewed relevant `docs/*.md` and updated them OR confirmed no change is needed.
- [ ] For new or changed features, `docs/features/<feature>.md` accurately describes:
      - flows, states, and edge cases,
      - acceptance criteria that match the implemented behaviour.
- [ ] PR description includes a short “Docs” section:
      - `Docs: updated <list of files>` or
      - `Docs: no change (reason: …)`.

Keeping code and docs in sync is part of the definition of Done for this project.
